====Usage notes====
{{lang|ja|鬱}} has, at 29 strokes, the most strokes of any kanji in the jōyō kanji list or {{w|kanji kentei}} level 2.<ref>[http://nihonshock.com/2009/10/crazy-kanji-highest-stroke-count/ Crazy kanji: what’s the highest stroke count?], Nihonshock, 2009 Oct 22</ref> The next-highest kanji by stroke count in the jōyō list is {{m|ja|鑑}}, at 23 strokes.

Prior to the Japanese script reform, this character was handwritten as {{m|ja|欝}} using 25 strokes, similar to how {{m|ja|令}} is often written differently in handwriting. However, after the reform, the character became proscribed by being excluded from the official lists. In 2010, the character was reintroduced to the jōyō list, but only the print form was included and it is today taught to be written like the print form instead of like {{m|ja|欝}}.

Despite being reintroduced, the character is often written in hiragana, such as {{ja-r|うつ病|うつびょう}}. The NHK has officially promoted the use of these hiragana spellings.<ref>[https://www.nhk.or.jp/bunken/summary/kotoba/yougo/pdf/069.pdf 用語の決定], NHK, 2010 December</ref>

